article.description:
Leilani Estavan had 20 points, nine
assists and six steals as Oregon State beat  Arizona (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP) 71-65 in
overtime Thursday night.
article.headline: Estavan's strong all-around game key for Beavers
article.linkText: Pac-10 upset: Oregon State defeats Arizona in OT
article.story:
CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Leilani Estavan just couldn't get her shot
to fall. Luckily for Oregon State, she could do everything else.  

	   Estavan scored 12 of her 20 points from the free throw line to
add to her nine assists, and six steals as Oregon State knocked off
Arizona  (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP) 71-65 in overtime.

	   Estavan scored the last point of regulation and the first six of
overtime despite 4-of-17 shooting as the Beavers avenged a 72-44
loss in Tucson Jan.4.

	"In a game like that you have to have confidence," Estavan
said. "Weve been in a lot of overtime games and so we knew what to
do. You just have to dig deep."

	   Shawntinice Polk led the Wildcats with 18 points and 11
rebounds. Aimee Grzyb had 15 points and Dee-Dee Wheeler and Krista
Warren each had 12.

	   Oregon State (11-8, 5-5 Pac-10) also got 19 points and 11
rebounds from Hollye Chapman and 14 points and 10 rebounds from
Casey Bunn.

	   Arizona (13-6, 6-4) will likely drop out of the top-25 with the
loss.

	   "I thought we had momentum going into OT," said Arizona coach
Joan Bonvicini. "We kept them from scoring at the end of
regulation. It was a matter of our starters were exhausted and we
need better support from our bench."

	   Oregon State reduced its turnovers in the second half and shot
58 percent from the field to finish the game at 48 percent.

	 "I will tell you our players played so hard," said Oregon
State coach Judy Spoelstra. "There were times when they were
completely exhausted, but they just dug in with two minutes left
and said I am playing."

	   The Beavers committed 16 turnovers in the first half, but held a
22-8 rebounding edge.

	   Oregon State took an early 19-15 lead, but the Wildcats went on
a 10-2 run to take a 29-23 halftime advantage.

	   The Beavers went on an 8-0 run to open up the second half, and
led 54-50 at 5:55 on Bunns three-point play. Tied at 58-58, Arizona
went ahead on Grzybs three-point play at 2:19. But Brina Chaney hit
a jumper to make it 61-60 and Estavan hit a free throw to tie the
game.

	   Oregon State had a chance to win in regulation but Estavan drove
into the key and threw up an airball.
